{"type":"message","id":"5d709005","parentId":"094fe263","timestamp":"2026-07-05T15:39:44.032Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user says \"继续\" (continue). Let me check the current state:\n\n1. The service is running\n2. But the API response still shows `supported_levels: [\"1/25\", \"1/30000\"]` instead of the full list of 21 values from function.json\n\nThis suggests that the fix still hasn't applied correctly. Let me think about what might be wrong:\n\n1. The code change I made might not be working correctly\n2. The device_id might not be in the right format\n3. There might be an exception being caught silently\n\nLet me check:\n1. What is the `device_id` format? Looking at the code, `device_id` comes from the path parameter `/ptz/{device_id}/image/shutter`\n2. If the device_id is \"192.168.5.72\", then `DEVICES_DIR / \"192.168.5.72\"` would be wrong - it should be the MAC \"240f9b764193\"\n\nThe problem is that `device_id` in the path might be the IP address, not the MAC. Let me check how device_id is mapped in the router.\n\nLooking at the code, I see that there are several endpoints in router.py that accept `device_id`. Some accept `device_ip` and some accept `device_id`. The `get_shutter` endpoint accepts `device_id` as a path parameter, but it might be either the MAC or the IP.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The solution should be to:\n1. First try to use the `device_id` directly (as MAC)\n2. If that doesn't work, try to find the device by IP\n\nActually, looking at similar functions in router.py, I see that `device_id` is typically cleaned to a MAC format (remove colons and hyphens, lowercase). So \"240f:9b:76:41-93\" becomes \"240f9b764193\".\n\nBut the endpoint in the test is calling `/api/v1/ptz/192.168.5.72/image/shutter` with `device_id=\"192.168.5.72\"`, which is the IP address, not the MAC!\n\n\nI should modify the approach to handle IP address input directly. The current implementation fails when 